# capture.env — optional configuration for scripts/capture-legacy.sh
#
# Copy this file to `capture.env` (next to capture-legacy.sh) and fill in
# the values that apply at your site.  The wrapper sources this file on
# every invocation, so you don't need to re-export env vars in each shell.
#
# Everything here is optional.  If a variable is already exported in the
# shell that launches SAS, the export wins and this file is ignored for
# that variable.
#
# Alternate locations checked in order:
#   1. `capture.env` next to capture-legacy.sh (this file)
#   2. `$HOME/.hazard-capture.env`
#   3. Env vars exported in the shell
#   4. `$HAZAPPS`-based auto-detection (see below)

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Legacy binary paths
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# The wrapper stands in for `hazard` and `hazpred` on the SAS PATH.  Set
# these to the REAL binary locations so the wrapper can exec them after
# capturing the inputs.
#
# On sites where SAS pre-sets $HAZAPPS to the HAZARD install dir, you can
# leave these unset — the wrapper falls back to $HAZAPPS/hazard and
# $HAZAPPS/hazpred automatically.

# HAZARD_REAL=/usr/local/hazard-4.3.1/bin/hazard
# HAZPRED_REAL=/usr/local/hazard-4.3.1/bin/hazpred

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Capture drop zone
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Directory where the wrapper accumulates captured tuples.  Defaults to
# `$HOME/hazard-capture/` — consistent location regardless of which dir
# SAS was launched from.  Multiple capture sessions accumulate there
# safely (each tuple has a unique uid).
#
# Override if you want a timestamped dir per session, or a different root:

# HAZARD_CAPTURE_DIR="$HOME/hazard-capture/$(date +%Y%m%d-%H%M)"
# HAZARD_CAPTURE_DIR=/var/captures/hazard
